<DOC><DOCNO> AP880916-0079 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-09-16-88 0648EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r a PM-WeatherpageWeather     09-16 0561</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0576</SECOND><HEAD>Rain, Wind, Tides Herald Gilbert's Approach in Texas; Rain inPlains</HEAD><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   Heavy rain, gusty winds and high tides heralded the approach ofHurricane Gilbert along Texas' southern Gulf Coast today whileunrelated showers and thunderstorms soaked parts of the Plains.   Showers and scattered thunderstorms also extended to the lowerMississippi Valley, the central Gulf Coast and Florida.   Hurricane warnings were in effect along the southern Texas coastfrom Port O'Conner to Brownsville and south along the Mexican coastto Tampico. A hurricane watch was in effect eastward from PortO'Conner to Port Arthur, Texas, near Louisiana.   The first major rains from Gilbert hit Brownsville lateThursday, accompanied by wind gusts up to 40 mph, and CorpusChristi reported tides 3 to 4 feet above normal.   Out in the gulf today, the hurricane packed maximum sustainedwinds of 120 mph and 10- to 15-inch rainfall. Tides were expectedto run 7 to 11 feet above normal when Gilbert makes landfall.   A band of thunderstorms lashed the area from north Texas tonorthwest Missouri with heavy rains, strong winds and hailThursday. Power lines were downed, and golf ball-size hail peltedPonca City, Okla. By early today, the storms had dropped 1 to 2inches of rain in several locations.   Showers also dampened Iowa, Minnesota and the eastern parts ofSouth Dakota and Nebraska. Cloudy skies covered the PacificNorthwest, but it was clear in most other parts of the country.   Early morning temperatures dipped into the 30s and 40s in thenorthern Atlantic Coast, with frost warnings in effect for Vermontand eastern New York state.   Today's forecast called for numerous showers and thunderstormsfrom Hurricane Gilbert over southern Louisiana and Texas, withstrong gusty winds in southern Texas and the northern Rockies;showers and a few thunderstorms from South Carolina to the GulfCoast states, from the Tennessee, lower Ohio and Mississippivalleys to the eastern Plains, and over northern Michigan, northernWisconsin and eastern Minnesota; and widely scattered showers fromthe Pacific Northwest to northwest Montana.   Highs were forecast in the 70s and 80s over most of the nation;in the upper 50s and 60s in New England, the northern Appalachians,from northern Michigan to eastern Minnesota, and from northwestMontana to the Pacific Northwest and down part of the Californiacoast; in the lower 90s in Florida, Mississippi and parts of thesouthern Plains; and up to 105 degrees in the desert Southwest.   At 3 a.m. EDT, temperatures ranged from 34 degrees at Watertown,N.Y., to 84 degrees at Homestead, Fla.   Other reports:   _East: Atlanta 72 foggy; Boston 49 fair; Buffalo 44 fair;Charleston, S.C. 74 partly cloudy; Cincinnati 60 fair; Cleveland 51fair; Detroit 54 fair; Miami 83 partly cloudy; New York 54 fair;Philadelphia 52 fair; Pittsburgh 51 fair; Portland, Me. 43 fair;Washington 57 fair.   _Central: Bismarck 53 foggy; Chicago 61 fair; Dallas-Fort Worth77 fair; Denver 51 fair; Des Moines 66 rain; Indianapolis 62 fair;Kansas City 65 thunderstorms; Minneapolis-St. Paul 58 rain;Nashville 72 partly cloudy; New Orleans 79 foggy; St. Louis 72partly cloudy.   _West: Albuquerque 58 fair; Anchorage 53 cloudy; Las Vegas 72fair; Los Angeles 62 hazy; Phoenix 83 fair; Salt Lake City 62 fair;San Diego 65 cloudy; San Francisco 53 fair; Seattle 55 foggy.   _Canada: Montreal 45 fair; Toronto 45 fair.</TEXT></DOC>